<font color="#FF0000">ANSWER TO TOM</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jan  4 16:33:10 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
You are raising another point which should also be discussed.<br>
The paradox still exists.  A considerable number of Vietnamese did not want to be ruled by the communists as shown by the losses of perhaps a million Vietnamese fighting against them for 10 years before the Americans began taking over the fighting, during the American presence, and for two years after the Americans stopped fighting.  One side suppressed all protest, controlled the press, forced its young men to go to almost certain death, and won the war, while the other side permitted protest as a basic freedom and lost.  The protesters who were advocating a North Vietnamese victory, were, in effect, protesting a form of society that allowed them to protest.<br>
You have brought up a matter that many veterans bring up to explain why they decided the war was &quot;wrong&quot;.  The justification for protest generally involves the unnecessary loss of Americans´ lives due to the incompetence of the military services, grave injustices perpetrated by military or civilian officials, deliberate deceit of the public by elected officials and civil servants, and profiteering at the expense of the fighting men.  The basic evils in the government that permitted these things to happen would have existed whether or not the United States had gone to war in Vietnam.  The fact that the war was fought brought many of these things to light.  Did the protest movement help bring about reform?  I think that the opposite may have been true.<br>
Usually, after a debacle on the scale of the Vietnam War, there would be a call for a thorough reform of the armed forces.  Instead, the senior careerists who had run the war from a safe distance and failed to come up with either a strategy or sound tactics actively began blaming the politicians, press, and protesters for their failure.  Since the protesters were saying that the war was wrong in the first place, nobody had to take any corrective action.  The politicians and senior civil servants escaped censure by claiming that they were against the war all the time.  From the recent statements of Robert McNamara, he is claiming to have decided that the war was unwinnable less than a year after he started sending combat troops there.  Thus, we are led to believe that he pressured Kennedy into having Diem deposed in 1963 in order to deploy more American troops in Vietnam and take charge of the war, and before he had finished deploying the troops he was responsible for sending, he was already saying that the war could not be won.  The record shows that many &quot;doves&quot; in Congress voted for the Gulf of Tonkin Resolution.  The cry that the war was &quot;wrong&quot; also came from many officials in the State Department.  Looking back, we see that the Vietnam War could have been avoided if the State Department had made correct assessments and recommendations at many times in the past.  For example, it was recommended that de Gaulle be appeased by helping the French reconquer their Indo-China colonies at a time when American officers were advising and training the Viet Minh. We deliberately abandoned our considerable influence over Ho Chi Minh´s government because we considered Europe &quot;more important&quot;.  Help for the French was denied at the critical moment during the Battle for Dien Bien Phu.  Laos was turned over to a &quot;neutralist&quot; government that allowed the eastern part of the country to be used for the supply routes of the North Vietnamese Army.  Diplomacy and the correct assessment of the importance of Eastern Asia might have prevented the whole debacle.  However, the same State Department that failed to achieve American goals without the need for military action has become one of the leading organizations of the Executive Branch in placing the blame for the war on the veterans, as attested to by the fact that this department has virtually excluded Vietnam Era veterans from employment.<br>
By propagating the maxim that the war was &quot;wrong&quot;, the protesters allowed a whole generation of slimy politicians, corrupt civil and military careerists, and salesmen of defective equipment to escape scrutiny of their activities and retire with &quot;super&quot; pensions and benefits.<br>
In fact, five consecutive elected presidents publicly pronounced that the Vietnam War was essential for the national security of the United States to contain Soviet and Communist Chinese expansion during the Cold War, and they each increased the American commitment.  For more than a decade, a freely elected Congress voted by overwhelming majorities for the legislation to support the commitment of men and money for keeping the communists from taking over South Vietnam.  The Executive departments and agencies assigned the job of conducting the war told the Congress repeatedly that the war could be won.  By directing the protest at the war rather than at the persons and agencies responsible for either deceiving the public about an unwinnable war or losing a winnable won through inefficiency and corruption, the protest movement smoothed the way from a bad wartime government to a bad peacetime government.<br>
There is a basic difference between an unjust cause and a just cause lost through bad leadership and corrupt institutions.  Proclaiming a lost cause to be unjust absolves the corrupt institutions from blame and permits many criminals to go unprosecuted.  For example, if McNamara was responsible for sending 58,000 Americans to die for a war which he helped get us into and then, for political reasons, went about seeing to it that we lost, is he not guilty a crime for which he should be prosecuted?  In fact, his actions have never even been investigated by a pubic prosecutor.<br><br>

